Yes — it can, but it depends on how the spreadsheet is pasted and how the prompt processes it. The issue is not simply “large input”; it’s how the model is instructed to reason about multiple rows. The good news is that you can paste the whole sheet without losing quality if you structure the prompt correctly.
The experts would recommend row-wise processing inside a single prompt. That keeps the reasoning isolated per change while still letting you paste the full spreadsheet once.
Why naïvely pasting the spreadsheet can reduce quality
If you simply paste the spreadsheet and say:
“Analyze these changes and generate descriptions and rationales.”
the model may:
• blend multiple changes together
• reuse rationale across rows
• infer relationships between unrelated changes
• miss rows or produce uneven output
This happens because the model treats the spreadsheet as one reasoning problem instead of many small problems.
The correct approach: Row-wise processing
Instead, you instruct the model to treat each row independently.
Conceptually:
Copy code

Row 1 → analyze → output
Row 2 → analyze → output
Row 3 → analyze → output
Even though the spreadsheet is pasted once.
This is essentially a Map-style workflow applied within one prompt.
Recommended prompt structure for your spreadsheet
You can paste the entire spreadsheet under this prompt.
Writing
Assume the roles of the following experts:
• Clinical Scientist
• Regulatory Medical Writer
• Protocol Operations Reviewer
• Reasoning Validator
Objective: Analyze proposed protocol amendment changes and generate text for a protocol amendment "Summary of Changes" table.
Each change should produce:
A concise Description of Change (Column 2 of the table)
A brief Rationale for Change (Column 3 of the table)
Important instructions:
• Treat each row independently.
• Do not combine or compare rows.
• Do not assume relationships between changes unless explicitly stated.
• Use only the information provided in the row.
• If rationale is not explicit, provide a cautious, general explanation.
PROCESSING INSTRUCTIONS
You will receive a spreadsheet containing multiple proposed protocol changes.
Process the spreadsheet row by row.
For each row:
STEP 1
Interpret the proposed change.
STEP 2
Generate a concise Description of Change suitable for a protocol amendment Summary of Changes table.
STEP 3
Generate a brief Rationale explaining the likely purpose of the change.
Keep both outputs concise and regulatory-appropriate.
OUTPUT FORMAT
Return a structured table with the following columns:
Row Number
Original Change Description
Description of Change
Rationale for Change
SPREADSHEET INPUT
[PASTE THE EXCEL ROWS HERE]
